This paper deals with optimization problems related to vehicle routing and scheduling, which are typically studied in the fields of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), robotics (cs.RO), and machine learning (cs.LG) for their practical applications. The problem formulation also involves metric spaces and graph theory, which are relevant to the subfield of computational geometry (cs.CG) and theoretical computer science (cs.TH). However, since the focus of the paper is on designing approximation algorithms for the problem, rather than proving theoretical bounds, we consider cs.SI (social and information networks) as the least likely sub-category.
